data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code is the **Timeout enforcement** pattern. Here's what's broken in .NET 8:

| API | .NET 8 Status |
|-----|---------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires (abort can't be raised) |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(work, timeout, CancellationToken.None);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout,
                                    CancellationToken externalToken)
    {
        // Link external token with a timeout-based token
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var token = cts.Token;
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            // Available in .NET 6+
            task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // If the work threw, unwrap and rethrow
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw new AggregateException(task.Exception!.InnerExceptions);

        return task.Result;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter()`** — cooperative cancellation replaces forced termination
2. **`ThreadAbortException` → `OperationCanceledException`** — the new signal type
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — no equivalent needed
4. **`Thread` → `Task.Run`** — uses the thread pool instead of manual threads

## ⚠️ Critical Pitfall: Uncooperative Work

The **fundamental paradigm shift** is from preemptive to cooperative cancellation. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop or blocking call that never checks the token, **cancellation won't stop it** — the task keeps running in the background even after you throw `TimeoutException`.

**If `work` cooperates** (best case) — pass the token through:

```csharp
// Caller passes cancellation-aware work
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeResult(cts.Token),  // checks token internally
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**If `work` can't cooperate** (e.g., third-party library, native call) — move it to a child process and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no safe in-process alternative to `Thread.Abort`.

## Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|------------|
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Always `using` — leaks timers otherwise |
| `Task.Run` fire-and-forget on timeout | The task continues running; log/observe its eventual fault |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from caller cancellation |
| Assuming immediate stop | Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside `work` |
